# Environment file for examples/compose/ — copy to .env and edit.
#
# `docker compose up` (in this directory) auto-loads .env. The values
# below mirror the env vars referenced in docker-compose.yml.
#
# Most fields are optional. Anthropic API key is required only if you
# want the claude-container service to talk to the real API.

# --- claude-container --------------------------------------------------

# Anthropic API key. Leave empty to bring the container up without
# making API calls (useful for testing the tmux entrypoint).
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=

# Optional: VSCode IDE integration port (HTTP/SSE on host loopback).
# Set if you want the in-container claude binary to dial your host's
# VSCode SSE listener; otherwise leave unset.
# CLAUDE_CODE_SSE_PORT=

# --- queue-minisite branding (optional) -------------------------------
#
# The public image renders as generic "queue" with the bundled
# claude-watch eye-glyph if QUEUE_SITE_LOGO_DEFAULT=1. Override these
# to brand the deployment. Empty = bundled default.

# QUEUE_SITE_TITLE=queue
# QUEUE_SITE_LOGO_URL=
# QUEUE_SITE_LOGO_DEFAULT=1
# QUEUE_SITE_BRAND=
# QUEUE_SITE_FAVICON_URL=

# --- eichi search-minisite branding (optional) ------------------------

# SEARCH_SITE_TITLE=eichi search
# SEARCH_SITE_LOGO_URL=
# SEARCH_SITE_LOGO_DEFAULT=1
# SEARCH_SITE_BRAND=
# SEARCH_SITE_FAVICON_URL=

# --- Host-state bind-mount source paths (Phase 2) ---------------------
#
# The claude-container service bind-mounts a curated subset of host state
# into the container so the in-container claude / claude-watch boot with
# real config instead of vanilla defaults. By default each source path
# resolves to the standard Linux location under ${HOME} (or /etc for the
# managed-settings tier). Override below if your host layout differs —
# which is the typical case on macOS, where Claude Code's managed-settings
# tier lives under /Library/Application Support/ClaudeCode/ instead of
# /etc/claude-code/.
#
# Managed-settings note: whatever host dir you point
# CLAUDE_HOST_MANAGED_SETTINGS_DIR at is mounted read-only at the fixed
# in-container staging path /mnt/host-managed-claude-config, and its
# managed-settings.json surfaces at /etc/claude-code/managed-settings.json
# (the Linux managed-config path the in-container claude reads) via a
# symlink the entrypoint creates CONDITIONALLY at startup (only when a
# readable managed-settings.json is actually present under the staging
# mount; otherwise the link is removed so the tier is cleanly absent). So
# the macOS path works fine as a SOURCE — the container side is always the
# correct Linux location. Unset = no managed-settings tier in the container.
#
# DEPLOY-DIR GOTCHA: docker compose auto-loads `.env` from the deploy dir
# (examples/compose/), but `.env` is gitignored and so is ABSENT in a build
# worktree (`~/repos/.worktrees/claude-watch/main`) — the path the deploy
# workflow uses. A var set ONLY here therefore vanishes on a worktree
# deploy, silently defaulting CLAUDE_HOST_MANAGED_SETTINGS_DIR to the
# /dev/null mount. To opt into managed settings reliably regardless of
# which clone/worktree deploys, ALSO set it in the location-independent
# config-dir env-file ~/.config/claude-container/deploy.env — the Makefile
# `deploy-container` target passes that file via `--env-file`. One-time
# migration: `mkdir -p ~/.config/claude-container && echo
# 'CLAUDE_HOST_MANAGED_SETTINGS_DIR=<your-dir>' >>
# ~/.config/claude-container/deploy.env`.
#
# Per Claude Code's settings precedence (highest -> lowest, see
# https://code.claude.com/docs/en/settings):
#
#   Tier                       env var                          Linux default                  macOS default
#   --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#   Managed / enterprise       CLAUDE_HOST_MANAGED_SETTINGS_DIR /etc/claude-code              /Library/Application Support/ClaudeCode
#   User-global (~/.claude)    CLAUDE_HOST_CONFIG_DIR           $HOME/.claude                 $HOME/.claude (same)
#   User-global (~/.claude.json) CLAUDE_HOST_CONFIG_FILE        $HOME/.claude.json            $HOME/.claude.json (same)
#   Project-level (.claude/)   (via repos mount; no env var)    $HOME/repos                   $HOME/repos
#
# Operator tooling / event-spool paths (not Claude Code tiers, but
# bind-mounted alongside so the in-container claude-watch sees the same
# surface as the host):
#
#   CLAUDE_HOST_REPOS_DIR          host repo trees    default: $HOME/repos
#   CLAUDE_HOST_BIN_DIR            host shim scripts  default: $HOME/bin
#   CLAUDE_HOST_EVENTS_DIR         claude-event spool default: /dev/null
#                                                     (mirror; see notes below)
#   CLAUDE_HOST_OBLIGATIONS_DIR    operator obligation manifests
#                                                     default: /dev/null
#                                                     (see notes below)
#
# Per-tier user-level paths (~/.claude and ~/.claude.json) are the SAME
# on Linux and macOS per the Claude Code docs — they're listed here for
# completeness in case a deployment intentionally relocates them.
#
# .env values support whitespace literally — quote only if you want the
# quotes preserved. Example macOS overrides:
#
#   CLAUDE_HOST_MANAGED_SETTINGS_DIR=/Library/Application Support/ClaudeCode
#   CLAUDE_HOST_CONFIG_DIR=$HOME/.claude
#   CLAUDE_HOST_CONFIG_FILE=$HOME/.claude.json
#
# Docker Desktop note (macOS): paths outside Docker Desktop's default
# file-sharing allowlist (/Users, /tmp, /private, /var/folders) need to
# be explicitly added via Docker Desktop -> Resources -> File Sharing
# before they can be bind-mounted. /Library/Application Support/...
# is one such path — add it on first launch if you override
# CLAUDE_HOST_MANAGED_SETTINGS_DIR.
#
# Host-specific integration mounts (shell-history DBs, messaging
# attachment dirs, etc.) are intentionally NOT wired here — add them
# via a local docker-compose.override.yml if you need them.
#
# Leave all commented out to keep the Linux defaults.

# CLAUDE_HOST_MANAGED_SETTINGS_DIR=/etc/claude-code
# CLAUDE_HOST_CONFIG_DIR=$HOME/.claude
# CLAUDE_HOST_CONFIG_FILE=$HOME/.claude.json
# CLAUDE_HOST_REPOS_DIR=$HOME/repos
# CLAUDE_HOST_BIN_DIR=$HOME/bin
# CLAUDE_HOST_EVENTS_DIR=$HOME/claude-events

# --- Operator obligation manifests (CLAUDE_HOST_OBLIGATIONS_DIR) ------
# Point at a host dir of *.json obligation-row manifests (one row per
# file; schema mirrors `obligations add`). obligations-init applies each
# idempotently on EVERY container start, AFTER the baked container-policy
# default rows — so operator-specific obligations (e.g. the
# AskUserQuestion presence-gate) are DECLARATIVE private config, never
# baked into the shared image, never `register`-ed per session. Read-only
# mount; default /dev/null is a clean no-op (absent / empty / non-dir =
# "no user obligations"). See README "Operator obligation manifests".
# CLAUDE_HOST_OBLIGATIONS_DIR=$HOME/.config/claude-container/obligations

# --- macOS: container .claude.json must be a dedicated file ----------
# On Docker Desktop for Mac, do NOT leave CLAUDE_HOST_CONFIG_FILE at the
# default $HOME/.claude.json. That is a single-file bind mount, and the
# host's native Claude Code rewrites ~/.claude.json (new inode) on every
# settings change — the VirtioFS/gRPC-FUSE mount stays pinned to the old
# inode and the in-container claude reads stale / truncated content.
# Point it at a dedicated container-only file instead; `cw --up` seeds it
# once from ~/.claude.json (preserving project trust, MCP registry, model
# prefs) via bin/prepare-host-claude-state, and the container owns it
# thereafter. Linux hosts don't need this (file bind mounts don't desync).
# CLAUDE_HOST_CONFIG_FILE=$HOME/.config/claude-container/claude.json
#
# macOS auth: `cw --up` also bridges the login Keychain's Claude token
# ("Claude Code-credentials") into ~/.claude/.credentials.json, since on
# macOS the live OAuth token lives in the Keychain, not on disk — without
# this the in-container claude starts logged out. Fail-closed: a locked
# keychain or missing host login aborts `cw --up`.

# --- Claude event spool bridging (CLAUDE_HOST_EVENTS_DIR) ------------
#
# The claude-event spool (the directory where host cron / alertmanager
# / queue producers drop JSON events for the in-container claude-event-
# tail watcher to surface to the session) uses a SAME-PATH-ON-BOTH-
# SIDES mirror pattern: the host source and the in-container
# destination are the SAME absolute path. The in-container watcher
# resolves the path via the CLAUDE_EVENT_QUEUE env var, which compose
# wires from the same CLAUDE_HOST_EVENTS_DIR value, so both ends agree
# without depending on $HOME resolution.
#
# Why mirror: when an operator runs `sudo docker compose up`, Compose
# resolves ${HOME} to /root. The pre-2026-05-16 default of
# ${HOME}/claude-events silently bridged to /root/claude-events
# instead of the operator's actual spool. The mirror pattern (set the
# var explicitly to your spool path) sidesteps that foot-gun.
#
# Default: unset → bind-mounts /dev/null at /dev/null (graceful no-op)
# and the in-container watcher falls back to the in-container default
# of $HOME/claude-events (= /home/hndrewaall/claude-events, with no
# host bridging). Operators who DO want host claude-event bridging set
# the var to their host spool path; that same path appears inside the
# container and the watcher picks it up automatically.
#
# Example (Linux host whose operator user is `andrew`):
#   CLAUDE_HOST_EVENTS_DIR=/home/andrew/claude-events
#
# Example (macOS host):
#   CLAUDE_HOST_EVENTS_DIR=/Users/andrew/claude-events
#
# Tighter shapes (downstream image, alternative spool layout, etc.)
# can override CLAUDE_EVENT_QUEUE independently — the compose service
# forwards whatever value is supplied, so a downstream override of
# CLAUDE_EVENT_QUEUE wins over the default wiring above.

# --- Corporate-network passthrough (SSL + proxy) ----------------------
#
# Operators on enterprise VPNs typically have a corp
# root CA injected into NODE_EXTRA_CA_CERTS (and friends) on the host.
# Without forwarding these, the in-container claude binary fails any
# TLS handshake behind the corp MITM proxy with
# "Unable to connect to API: SSL certificate verification failed.
# Check your proxy or corporate SSL certificates".
#
# Two things have to happen for SSL passthrough to work:
#
#   1. The env var has to make it into the container (handled by the
#      `environment:` block in docker-compose.yml — set NODE_EXTRA_CA_CERTS
#      etc. in this .env file and compose substitutes them).
#   2. The CA bundle file path has to resolve INSIDE the container.
#      Set CLAUDE_HOST_CORP_CA_BUNDLE below to the host path of your
#      corp CA bundle; compose bind-mounts it read-only at the SAME path
#      inside the container so the env-var reference resolves.
#
# Set NODE_EXTRA_CA_CERTS to the SAME absolute path as
# CLAUDE_HOST_CORP_CA_BUNDLE. Node / openssl / curl / python requests
# all honor variants of this env var; the example below covers Claude
# Code's Node runtime + Python tooling in one shot.
#
# Proxy env vars (HTTPS_PROXY / HTTP_PROXY / NO_PROXY) are just
# forwarded — the proxy hostname needs to be reachable from the
# container's netns. host.docker.internal is wired via extra_hosts,
# so a host-loopback corp proxy works without extra config.
#
# Leave commented out if you're not on a corp VPN.

# NODE_EXTRA_CA_CERTS=/Users/<you>/.config/corp/corp-ca.pem
# SSL_CERT_FILE=/Users/<you>/.config/corp/corp-ca.pem
# REQUESTS_CA_BUNDLE=/Users/<you>/.config/corp/corp-ca.pem
# CURL_CA_BUNDLE=/Users/<you>/.config/corp/corp-ca.pem
# CLAUDE_HOST_CORP_CA_BUNDLE=/Users/<you>/.config/corp/corp-ca.pem
# HTTPS_PROXY=http://corp-proxy.example.com:8080
# HTTP_PROXY=http://corp-proxy.example.com:8080
# NO_PROXY=localhost,127.0.0.1,host.docker.internal

# --- Host hook-script dir --------------------------------------------
#
# When ~/.claude/settings.json references hook scripts by ABSOLUTE host
# path (corp telemetry hooks, auto-installed via a corporate telemetry tool),
# the path has to resolve inside the container or Claude Code prints
# "SessionStart:startup hook error — /bin/sh: 1: <path>: not found"
# and refuses to fire the hook. Set CLAUDE_HOST_HOOKS_DIR to the host
# directory containing those hook scripts; compose bind-mounts it
# read-only at the SAME path inside the container so the settings.json
# reference Just Works.
#
# Example (macOS, corp-tool-installed corp telemetry hook):
#   CLAUDE_HOST_HOOKS_DIR=/Users/<you>/.local/bin

# CLAUDE_HOST_HOOKS_DIR=/Users/<you>/.local/bin

# --- Cross-arch hook auto-rewrite ------------------------------------
#
# On a Mac host whose ~/.claude/settings.json bind-mounts hook commands
# pointing at Mach-O / arm64 binaries (telemetry hooks etc.), Linux's
# exec() bounces them with "Exec format error" and Claude Code logs the
# failure on every hook event. The image bakes /usr/local/bin/exec-hook
# (a magic-byte sniffer that transparently exec's ELF and silently no-ops
# on Mach-O / unknown formats) — but the wiring is opt-in.
#
# Set CLAUDE_CONTAINER_REWRITE_HOOKS=1 to have the entrypoint generate a
# container-local copy of settings.json with every hook command wrapped
# in /usr/local/bin/exec-hook, then launch claude with
# `--setting-sources project,local --settings /tmp/claude-shim/settings.json`.
# The `--setting-sources` flag drops the bind-mounted host user-tier
# settings.json from Claude Code's settings cascade so the bare cross-arch
# hooks don't ALSO load alongside the wrapped ones (Claude Code's
# `--settings` flag merges additively otherwise). The shim file preserves
# the host file's env / permissions / other top-level keys, so dropping
# the user tier doesn't lose anything else.
#
# Same path ALSO writes a project-tier `.mcp.json` into
# CLAUDE_HOST_PROJECT_DIR (below) so MCP server definitions survive
# the `--setting-sources project,local` filter. Claude Code v2.1.141
# does NOT read MCP server definitions from any settings.json tier —
# it loads them from ~/.claude.json via a code path gated on the
# `user` tier being in --setting-sources. Filtering `user` out (to
# drop bare host hooks) also suppresses MCP discovery, so v21 workbot
# saw "No MCP servers configured" inside the container even though
# /mcp on the host worked fine.
#
# Fix: the entrypoint runs `generate-project-mcp-json` to write
# `${CLAUDE_HOST_PROJECT_DIR}/.mcp.json` populated from
# ~/.claude.json's mcpServers (top-level + projects.<host-path>),
# wrapping each server's `command` with /usr/local/bin/exec-hook.
# Project tier IS in `--setting-sources project,local`, and `.mcp.json`
# is Claude Code's standard project-level MCP config file. ELF /
# shebang-script servers (node / python / Linux binaries) run
# normally; Mach-O / unknown-format servers silently no-op (server
# fails to start but no "Exec format error" spam). The host
# ~/.claude.json is never mutated.
#
# Requires CLAUDE_HOST_PROJECT_DIR (below) to be set. If the project
# dir is a git tree, consider gitignoring `.mcp.json` — the file is
# container-only and references /usr/local/bin/exec-hook, which
# doesn't exist on the host.
#
# Default off so existing operators see no behaviour change.

# CLAUDE_CONTAINER_REWRITE_HOOKS=1

# --- Generic shim-pattern filter (CLAUDE_SHIM_PATTERNS) --------------
#
# When CLAUDE_CONTAINER_REWRITE_HOOKS=1, the default behaviour is to
# wrap EVERY hook command + EVERY MCP server `command` with
# /usr/local/bin/exec-hook. That's safe (the shim is transparent on
# ELF / shebang; only Mach-O / unknown formats no-op), but operators
# can narrow the set of commands the rewrite touches by setting
# CLAUDE_SHIM_PATTERNS to a colon-separated list of glob patterns.
# When set to a non-empty value, ONLY commands whose first
# whitespace-separated token (the binary path) matches at least one
# glob get wrapped; the rest pass through verbatim.
#
# Matching uses Python's fnmatch.fnmatchcase — standard shell
# wildcards (*, ?, [abc]), case-sensitive. Separator is `:` (parallel
# to PATH); paths containing literal `:` are rare on real systems but
# if you have one, use a more specific pattern that doesn't depend on
# the colon.
#
# Default (unset or empty) = wrap everything (backward-compatible
# with pre-PR-#147 behaviour). Common narrow values:
#
#   # Wrap only corp telemetry hooks under corp-tool paths:
#   CLAUDE_SHIM_PATTERNS=/Users/*/.local/bin/*:/Users/*/.local/pkgs/*/bin/*
#
#   # Wrap only the host-mcp-server MCP server binary:
#   CLAUDE_SHIM_PATTERNS=/Users/*/.host-mcp-server/bin/*
#
#   # Wrap any binary anywhere under /Users (broad):
#   CLAUDE_SHIM_PATTERNS=/Users/*
#
# The env var is consumed by both generate-hooks-shim-settings (hook
# commands) and generate-project-mcp-json (MCP server commands); the
# entrypoint passes it through verbatim to both helpers.

# CLAUDE_SHIM_PATTERNS=/Users/*/.local/bin/*:/Users/*/.local/pkgs/*/bin/*

# --- HTTP MCP bridge for cross-arch host binaries (CLAUDE_MCP_HTTP_BRIDGE) ---
#
# When an MCP server in your ~/.claude.json mcpServers points at a
# host-only binary that won't run inside the Linux container — typical
# case: a macOS Mach-O binary like a corporate host-mcp-server (e.g.
# /Users/<you>/.host-mcp-server/bin/host-mcp-server-bin-vX.Y.Z-darwin-arm64) —
# the default behaviour (wrap with exec-hook → silent no-op on Mach-O
# → "Failed to reconnect: ENOENT" in /mcp) keeps the container quiet
# but leaves that server unusable.
#
# The escape hatch: run a tiny HTTP→stdio adapter on the HOST that
# owns the actual MCP binary and exposes it on a TCP port (e.g.
# http://host.docker.internal:8765/mcp). Then set
# CLAUDE_MCP_HTTP_BRIDGE to a colon-separated list of `name=url`
# pairs; the entrypoint rewrites those entries in the container's
# .mcp.json from stdio shape to Claude Code's native HTTP transport
# (`type: "http"`, `url: <url>`). The in-container claude dials the
# host adapter instead of trying to exec the cross-arch binary.
#
# Pair this with a stdio→HTTP wrapper such as `mcp-proxy`,
# `mcphost`, the upstream `@modelcontextprotocol/sdk` helpers, or a
# hand-rolled shim. The host adapter is OUT OF SCOPE for this repo —
# wire it up via launchd / a manual `mcp-proxy` invocation / etc.
#
# Matching is by exact MCP server name (NOT command path). Unknown /
# unset = no rewriting (servers stay in stdio + exec-hook shape).
# Multiple pairs: separate with `:` (parallel to PATH).
#
# Example (single server):
#   CLAUDE_MCP_HTTP_BRIDGE=host-mcp-server=http://host.docker.internal:8765/mcp
#
# Example (multiple servers, colon-separated):
#   CLAUDE_MCP_HTTP_BRIDGE=host-mcp-server=http://host.docker.internal:8765/mcp:other=http://host.docker.internal:9000/mcp
#
# Example (host-mcp-server + the bundled `host-bash` generic-command MCP server
# — see the next block for the host-side launcher):
#   CLAUDE_MCP_HTTP_BRIDGE=host-mcp-server=http://host.docker.internal:8765/mcp:host-bash=http://host.docker.internal:8766/mcp

# CLAUDE_MCP_HTTP_BRIDGE=host-mcp-server=http://host.docker.internal:8765/mcp

# --- host-bash: generic "run a bash command on the host" MCP server -----
#
# Companion to the bridge above. Gives the in-container claude a single
# `run_command` tool that exec's argv on the HOST (not the container), so
# the container can drive host-only operations (corp git, host-only CLIs,
# scripts under the operator's home dir) without needing those binaries
# installed inside the Linux container.
#
# Architecture (no code in the container — all bridge name-keyed plumbing
# is already in place from CLAUDE_MCP_HTTP_BRIDGE above):
#
#   container claude               host
#   ────────────────              ────
#   .mcp.json: host-bash, type=http
#         │
#         ▼ (HTTP, streamable)
#   http://host.docker.internal:8766/mcp ─► mcp-proxy --port 8766
#                                                │
#                                                ▼ (stdio)
#                                            cli-mcp-server
#                                                │
#                                                ▼ (subprocess)
#                                            the actual command
#
# Both `mcp-proxy` and `cli-mcp-server` are statically installed once
# via `examples/compose/bin/install-host-deps` (which runs `uv tool
# install`); the launcher exec's them directly with NO per-launch
# network fetch. Earlier versions called `uvx mcp-proxy` / `uvx
# cli-mcp-server` and re-resolved from PyPI on every start — slow,
# fragile, and broken under corp-CA at launch time.
#
# Operator-side setup (one-time):
#
#   1. Make sure `host-bash` exists as an entry in your host's
#      ~/.claude.json mcpServers (the bridge rewrites by NAME, so the
#      entry MUST exist for the rewrite to fire). Easiest way:
#
#          claude mcp add host-bash echo placeholder
#
#      (the command/args are dropped on bridge rewrite — only the name
#      matters).
#
#   2. Install the host-side dependencies once (idempotent — re-running
#      is safe and cheap; pass `--upgrade` to force-refresh):
#
#          examples/compose/bin/install-host-deps
#
#      This runs `uv tool install mcp-proxy cli-mcp-server`. Corp-CA
#      operators: set SSL_CERT_FILE / REQUESTS_CA_BUNDLE / UV_NATIVE_TLS=1
#      in your shell first; the launcher itself never touches PyPI so
#      you won't see TLS errors at launch.
#
#   3. Start the host-side adapter (foreground in a tmux pane / launchd
#      job / etc.):
#
#          examples/compose/bin/mcp-host-bash
#
#      Default port: 8766. See `examples/compose/bin/mcp-host-bash --help`
#      for the full env-var / config-file surface.
#
#   4. Set CLAUDE_MCP_HTTP_BRIDGE in this .env file to include host-bash
#      (see the multi-server example two blocks up). Rebuild + restart
#      the container (`docker compose down && docker compose up -d`).
#
#   5. Inside the container: `claude mcp list` should show `host-bash:
#      Connected`. The tool is `mcp__host_bash__run_command` (or whatever
#      cli-mcp-server names it).
#
# Security: `run_command` is a substantial privilege escalation. The
# in-container claude can now exec code on the host. The
# `cli-mcp-server` allow-list is your safety floor:
#
#   ALLOWED_COMMANDS — comma-separated binary names. NEVER set to "all"
#                      in production. Default (in mcp-host-bash) is the
#                      read-y / observation / standard-dev-tool floor:
#                      file inspection (ls/cat/head/tail/grep/find/file/
#                      stat/diff/sort/uniq/wc), text munging (awk/sed/
#                      cut/tr/xargs/base64/jq/yq), VCS (git/gh), shell
#                      discovery (pwd/echo/which/env/printenv/hostname/
#                      uname/date/basename/dirname), language toolchains
#                      (node/npm/yarn/python/python3/pip/make), corp-dev
#                      binaries (envchain/jenkins-builds), read-y
#                      network probes (ping/host/dig/
#                      nslookup). Destructive / scheduling / outbound-
#                      bytes / key-material / container-mgmt binaries
#                      (docker / docker-compose) are gated behind
#                      CW_PROFILE=corp-dev-trusted (see mcp-host-bash).
#                      With CW_PROFILE=corp-dev-trusted the in-container
#                      claude can run `docker compose up -d
#                      --force-recreate <svc>` and `docker compose exec
#                      <svc> ...` from inside its own session.
#   ALLOWED_FLAGS    — comma-separated flag whitelist OR "all".
#   ALLOWED_DIR      — absolute path; the server refuses commands that
#                      resolve outside this tree. Default: $HOME.
#   COMMAND_TIMEOUT  — per-command wall-clock cap (s). Default: 30.
#   MAX_COMMAND_LENGTH — max single-command length (chars) before
#                      cli-mcp-server truncates. Default: 8192 (raised
#                      from cli-mcp-server's 1024 hardcoded default).
#   ALLOW_SHELL_OPERATORS — "true" enables pipes / && / ||. Default
#                      "false" (block command-chaining).
#
# Override per-host via a config file at
# ~/.config/claude-container/mcp-host-bash.env (plain KEY=VALUE lines).
# Example (broader allow-list for a corp-dev workflow):
#
#   # ~/.config/claude-container/mcp-host-bash.env
#   ALLOWED_COMMANDS=git,gh,make,npm,yarn,kubectl
#   ALLOWED_DIR=/Users/me/work
#   COMMAND_TIMEOUT=120
#   MAX_COMMAND_LENGTH=8192
#
# Bearer-token authentication
#
# `mcp-proxy` upstream has no inbound-auth feature, so the launcher
# can front it with `mcp-proxy-auth-shim` (a tiny stdlib-only reverse
# proxy that validates `Authorization: Bearer <secret>` on every
# request). To enable, set MCP_HOST_BASH_BEARER on the HOST launcher
# side AND CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_BEARER (below) in this .env file
# to the SAME value:
#
#   1. Generate a secret once. Keep this out of version control.
#        head -c 32 /dev/urandom | base64
#   2. Export on the host before launching mcp-host-bash:
#        export MCP_HOST_BASH_BEARER="<paste-the-secret>"
#   3. Set CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_BEARER in this .env (no export, no
#      quotes around the value — compose .env files are KEY=VAL):
#        CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_BEARER=<paste-the-same-secret>
#
# Both must be the same secret string. The shim FAILS CLOSED — if
# MCP_HOST_BASH_BEARER is unset/empty on the launcher side, the shim
# refuses to start (no silent fall-through to no-auth).
#
# When the launcher boots with a bearer set, mcp-proxy binds an
# internal loopback port (default: MCP_HOST_BASH_PORT+1, override
# via MCP_HOST_BASH_UPSTREAM_PORT) and the shim binds the public
# port (MCP_HOST_BASH_BIND:MCP_HOST_BASH_PORT). Callers without the
# bearer get 401'd by the shim; mcp-proxy never sees the request.
#
# Bare `--host 0.0.0.0` WITHOUT a bearer is the audit-flagged
# worst-case profile (LAN-exposed, no auth). The launcher banner
# warns loudly when it detects that shape.

# CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_BEARER=

# Bind address
#
# mcp-host-bash binds mcp-proxy to 127.0.0.1 (loopback only) by default.
# That is the safe floor: `run_command` is a host-shell privilege
# escalator, so anything reachable on the port can exec binaries on the
# host as the operator user. Default-deny LAN / sibling-container /
# sibling-uid exposure unless the operator explicitly opts in.
#
# Set MCP_HOST_BASH_BIND in the LAUNCHER's environment (NOT this .env
# file — this .env file feeds the docker-compose service, not the host
# launcher) to widen the listener. Typical opt-in shapes:
#
#   # Linux host with the in-container claude on the default Docker
#   # bridge network — host.docker.internal routes via docker0
#   # (172.17.0.1), which cannot reach host loopback. Bind 0.0.0.0 AND
#   # gate access with the bearer token (above).
#   MCP_HOST_BASH_BIND=0.0.0.0
#
#   # Pin to a specific interface IP (tighter than 0.0.0.0 — only
#   # exposes that interface):
#   MCP_HOST_BASH_BIND=172.17.0.1
#
# Linux containers using `--network host` skip this entirely — they
# share the host netns and can reach 127.0.0.1:8766 directly. macOS
# Docker Desktop's host.docker.internal NAT routes loopback for the
# default network setup, so the safe loopback default Just Works for
# the typical Mac compose stack.
#
# Kill switch: export MCP_HOST_BASH_DISABLED=1 in the shell that owns
# the adapter before invoking the launcher — refuses to start, exits 0.
# Useful as a "soft off" in a launchd plist or login-startup script.
#
# Auditing: mcp-proxy logs each request to its stderr; cli-mcp-server
# logs the resolved argv per `run_command`. The launcher tees both into
# ~/.local/state/claude-container/mcp-host-bash.log so you can audit
# what the container actually invoked.
#
# Abuse risk if the container is compromised: anyone with API access to
# the in-container claude can issue arbitrary tool calls. With a tight
# allow-list (read-only binaries + git) the blast radius stays
# contained; with `ALLOWED_COMMANDS=bash` or `ALLOWED_FLAGS=all` the
# container can do almost anything the host user could do. Tune the
# allow-list to what the container actually needs and audit the log.

# --- Cross-arch hook BRIDGE via host-bash MCP ------------------------
#
# Companion to CLAUDE_CONTAINER_REWRITE_HOOKS above. By default a
# Mac-host telemetry binary referenced from ~/.claude/settings.json
# silently no-ops inside the Linux container — exec-hook detects the
# Mach-O magic bytes and short-circuits to a 0-exit (the alternative,
# "Exec format error" on every hook event, is worse). That keeps the
# session usable but means real telemetry / corp hooks never actually
# fire from container sessions.
#
# Set CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE=1 to switch from "silent no-op" to
# "marshal across host-bash MCP". exec-hook hands every Mach-O /
# wrong-arch hook off to /usr/local/bin/exec-hook-bridge, which calls
# host-bash's `run_command` tool with the original target binary +
# args; the host runs the real binary (with forwarded env vars from
# Claude Code) and the exit code propagates back into the container so
# the in-container claude sees the same outcome as if the hook had run
# locally.
#
# Bridge failures (host-bash unreachable, allow-list reject, JSON-RPC
# error) fall back to the legacy silent-no-op contract — a
# misconfigured bridge never brings the session down. Each failure
# emits a one-line `[hook-bridge]` heads-up to stderr so operators can
# debug.
#
# Wire shape: the bridge speaks the MCP streamable-HTTP transport
# (mcp-proxy 0.11+). Each hook fire makes three sequential POSTs at
# the bridge URL:
#   1. `initialize` JSON-RPC request -> 200 + mcp-session-id header.
#   2. `notifications/initialized` JSON-RPC notification (with the
#      session header) -> 202 / empty body.
#   3. `tools/call` for cli-mcp-server's `run_command` (with the
#      session header) -> 200 + JSON / SSE body carrying stdout /
#      stderr / exit code.
# A stateless mcp-proxy (the `--stateless` flag) that doesn't issue a
# session id is also supported — the bridge omits the header on
# tools/call in that case.
#
# Requires the host-bash MCP server to be running (see the previous
# block) AND the hook binary's basename to be on cli-mcp-server's
# ALLOWED_COMMANDS allow-list. The simplest way to add it is via the
# CLAUDE_HOOK_BRIDGE_BINS env var on the host where mcp-host-bash
# runs — comma-separated basenames, merged into ALLOWED_COMMANDS at
# launcher start.
#
# Example (Mac operator with a corp telemetry hook at
# /Users/me/.local/bin/telemetry-hook):
#
#   # On the host, in the shell that launches mcp-host-bash:
#   export CLAUDE_HOOK_BRIDGE_BINS=telemetry-hook
#   examples/compose/bin/mcp-host-bash
#
#   # In this .env file:
#   CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE=1
#
# Optional knobs:
#   CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_URL       — full MCP endpoint. Default
#                                       http://host.docker.internal:8766/mcp
#   CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_TIMEOUT   — per-call seconds. Default 30.
#   CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_DEBUG     — `1` to log every JSON-RPC payload
#                                       to stderr (verbose).
#   CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_FORWARD_ENV
#                                     — colon-separated list of EXTRA
#                                       env vars to forward to the host
#                                       call (CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR,
#                                       CLAUDE_SESSION_ID,
#                                       CLAUDE_HOOK_EVENT,
#                                       CLAUDE_TRANSCRIPT_PATH are
#                                       always forwarded).
#
# Default off so existing operators see no behaviour change.

# CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE=1
# CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_URL=http://host.docker.internal:8766/mcp
# CLAUDE_HOST_HOOK_BRIDGE_TIMEOUT=30

# --- Host project dir (cwd / project-key match) ----------------------
#
# Claude Code's project memory tree is keyed off the cwd at launch:
#   ~/.claude/projects/<urlencoded-cwd>/memory/MEMORY.md
# On the host, cwd is the operator's actual project path
# (e.g. /Users/<you>/repos/eichi), which urlencodes to
# "-Users-<you>-repos-eichi". In the container, the default cwd is
# /workspace -> "-workspace", which has no matching entry in the bind-
# mounted ~/.claude/projects/ tree. The in-container claude reports
# "No previous memories found" even though the host tree is right
# there under the bind mount.
#
# Set CLAUDE_HOST_PROJECT_DIR to the ABSOLUTE host path you want as the
# in-container cwd. The wrapper bind-mounts that path at the SAME path
# inside the container AND sets it as the container WORKDIR, so Claude
# Code's project-key lookup matches the host. Trust pre-seeding (see
# trust-workspace.py) also covers the path so the in-container claude
# skips the first-launch trust dialog.
#
# PICK THE RIGHT DIR FOR MEMORY LOADING: if you typically launch claude
# from a WORKSPACE ROOT (~/repos) and only descend into sub-projects via
# slash-commands, your auto-memory tree lives at the workspace-root key
# (~/.claude/projects/-Users-<you>-repos/memory/), NOT at any per-project
# sub-key. Point CLAUDE_HOST_PROJECT_DIR at that workspace root, not at
# a specific sub-project, otherwise the in-container claude lands at a
# (typically empty) per-project memory tree. v19 workbot validation
# made this concrete: pointing at .../repos/eichi resolved the project
# key correctly but found no memory files because the actual auto-memory
# lives at the .../repos parent. Point at the parent to load workspace
# memories.
#
# Example (macOS, workspace-root for memory loading):
#   CLAUDE_HOST_PROJECT_DIR=/Users/<you>/repos
#
# Example (macOS, specific project — only set this when the project
# itself has its own ~/.claude/projects/<key>/ memory entries):
#   CLAUDE_HOST_PROJECT_DIR=/Users/<you>/repos/eichi

# CLAUDE_HOST_PROJECT_DIR=/Users/<you>/repos

# --- Site-specific host prep hook ------------------------------------
#
# Optional executable run by bin/prepare-host-claude-state (on `cw --up`
# and `make deploy-container`, alias `make redeploy`) AFTER the auth bridge + config seed, BEFORE
# `docker compose up -d`. Use it for site-specific prep you don't want in
# this public repo: refresh a corp API token into this .env, regenerate a
# sanitized managed-settings.json for the container, etc.
#
# Fail-closed: if set and the hook exits non-zero (or isn't executable),
# the up/redeploy ABORTS so the stack never starts with stale site config.
# Unset = no hook (default).
#
# CLAUDE_HOST_PREP_HOOK=/Users/<you>/path/to/private-host-prep

# --- Auto-resume the prior conversation on entry ---------------------
#
# When set to a non-empty value, the claude-container entrypoint appends
# `--continue "$value"` to the in-container claude invocation so the
# prior conversation auto-resumes with the value as the seed prompt.
# Matches the host alias shape:
#
#   #!/usr/bin/env bash
#   cd ~/repos && exec claude --continue "resume"
#
# Equivalent in-container behaviour: pair this with CLAUDE_HOST_PROJECT_DIR
# (above) so Claude Code's cwd-derived project key matches the host
# (otherwise the resume lands in the empty `/workspace` project bucket
# instead of the host's project memory tree).
#
# Default unset = bare claude (no auto-resume). Recommended value:
# `resume` (matches the standard host alias most operators already use).

# CLAUDE_AUTO_CONTINUE=resume
